metadata.name: I am rubber, you are glue #32
metadata.description:
The purpose of the artwork is to capture the gaze and stimulate the mind with it's synergy of geometric shapes and dynamic flows. I will try to lead you into an unexplored world where ellipses and rectangles form a vibrant grid, while a continuous flow of particles dances harmoniously within this abstract structure. The addition of a distinctive element, which I find fascinating, is the macram√®, providing a sense of connection between organic nature and the "digital nature."

The simple animation and interaction with the WASD keys were created to give a sense of constant movement and change without disrupting the canvas.

The use of color is carefully studied, with a subdued yet sophisticated palette, featuring delicate tones. This helps to keep the focus on the shapes and movement without excessive distractions.

Overall, the artwork aims to represent an example of how generative art can explore new aesthetic and narrative dimensions.

The functional keys are W, A, S, D, with a random tone. Press W to increase speed, press S to clear the frame.

To change the density from 1 to 8 (incorrect results set to 1), double-click the left mouse button.

I used p5.min.js - p5.sound.js.

P.S. The title comes from the witty and humorous dialogue typical of a famous 80s point-and-click video game:
"I am rubber, you are glue. A quote from my favorite macram√® artist."
It is a playful version of the well-known children's saying "I am rubber, you are glue, whatever you say bounces off me and sticks to you," but with a quirky twist involving macram√®.

metadata.name: Over the Air #584
metadata.description:
During the last couple of decades, over the air television signals and antennas switched to digital, bringing with them a new form of static and distortion as the signal is broken up. "Over the Air" is inspired by these digital distortions, incorporating aspects of them into the same grid-like structure seen on the television. Additional patterns are combined in the grid with these distortions to create the final artwork.

Patterns for the individual blocks in the grid are divided into categories, and various amounts are picked for each work, with dozens of possible mixtures. Patterns can flow in different directions across the varied canvases. Distribution of these patterns across the grid varies from work to work, providing for different feels as they bunch together or spread apart.

metadata.name: A Slight Case of Overbombing #16
metadata.description:
Inspired by monochromatic art of the late 60s, Russian folk-art woodblock prints, and the stylised colours of British underground comics, excited to introduce a series of bold rich landscapes. England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland represented by red, yellow, green and blue, sometimes a house or two, and groovy clouds.

Instructions ::

.     - speed up
,     - slow down
space - pause
n     - toggle noise
p     - cycle palette
h     - toggle high-res (and definitely intentional pixel shift)
s     - download and save image

metadata.name: Ghrian #335
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

Francesco Forcellini, November 2022, Milano, Italy.
Compositions of spheres made with grids, proportions, symmetries and  broken symmetries,  order and casualties.

To save a Hi-Resolution image 6000px x 8000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render.

Built using p5js,a custom WEBGL shader and a shader with a modified version of "cnoise" by Stefan Gustavson.

metadata.name: Sketches:Pairs of Tails:Majestic Creatures #29
metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.
